│   │  eth0   │     │  eth0   │     │  eth0   │                   │
│   └────┬────┘     └────┬────┘     └────┬────┘                   │
│        │               │               │                         │
│   ─────┴───────────────┴───────────────┴──────────────────────  │
│                  Docker Bridge (br-xxxx)                         │
│                  172.20.0.1 (gateway)                            │
│                            │                                     │
│                       ┌────┴─────┐                               │
│                       │   NAT    │                               │
│                       └────┬─────┘                               │
└────────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────────────────┘
                             │
                        Physical Network

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

KEY CONCEPTS
════════════
USER-DEFINED BRIDGE ADVANTAGES:
  1. Automatic DNS     - Containers resolve each other by name
  2. Better isolation  - Only connected containers communicate
  3. Hot-connect       - Add/remove containers without restart
  4. Configurable      - Custom subnets, gateways, options

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

VERIFICATION
════════════
Create a file called 'bridge_info.txt' with:
  Line 1: Frontend network subnet (e.g., 172.20.0.0/24)
  Line 2: Frontend network gateway (e.g., 172.20.0.1)
  Line 3: How many containers are on frontend_net? (a number)

Run: ./verify

Success: You understand bridge networks, can inspect them, and know the
difference between default and user-defined bridges.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

